column1: flash forward to the summer before freshman year and i got to go to a bbq with a bunch of other kids i had recently gone on a group trip with. ⁣
at that bbq .. we played night hide n seek in the dark.⁣
as i snuck towards a hiding spot
column2: he pinned me against the garage in that ally and shoved his disgusting

column1: he was a junior in high school.⁣
i was 14 and about to start my freshman year.⁣
he ripped my jeans open and reached his hand into them while pressing my hand against his own zipper making me feel something i knew nothing about. ⁣
my reality until then had been making up dances with my friends in my flowery pink bedroom...⁣
recording ourselves on boomboxes singing mariah carey’s someday and wilson phillips’ hold on...⁣
he stole my first kiss and made it frightening and disgusting and shameful.⁣
but i didn’t cower. i didn’t freeze.⁣
i shoved and shouted no!!!! and ran back to the house. sounds brave
but i never spoke of it. ⁣
i assumed it was my fault that my outgoing
column2: exuberant nature had sent him the wrong message that i wanted it.⁣

column1: i must have asked for it. right?⁣
what would people think of me and the way i had obviously (must have) misbehaved to bring something like this on?⁣
but i’ll betcha he doesn’t even remember that night?⁣
i’ll bet that the other kids who were there don’t remember that game of hide n seek
column2: nor the temperature of that end-of-the-summer night
column4: nor that the bbq even happened.⁣

column4: completely uninspired to type a word. i’ve been uninspired recently and that’s been something very difficult to admit. it’s been nearly impossible to be honest with myself... i’m uninspired because i’m exhausted. i’m completely emotionally drained. it seems like anytime i check a news outlet i’m triggered by a headline. i’m confused and i feel like i don’t recognize my own country. where do i live? my heart hurts for women all over. my heart hurts for any human who has ever been a victim of sexual assault. my heart hurts for my sixteen year old self. i’ve tried to imagine how it would feel to have the hands that violated my body then

column1: 308028;instagram;2018-10-07 20:05:49;FALSE;"our energetic fields have been greatly impacted this past week or maybe it’s been this last year. perhaps you’ve been feeling a little wobbly? disoriented or disconnected? not quite feeling like yourself?

column2: with the mass collective and with the stories of sexual abuse and violation. what we are needing is to support our energetic fields to differentiate and individualize. why? your energetic field is the bubble
column3: sphere that encompasses your physicality. it actually keeps you protected
column4: tethered to this incarnation and your body. it allows the fluidity of your emotions and all the waters in your being to move with ease and grace. it supports you to stay resourced and not become too porous that you live in overwhelm or exhaustion. but that’s what happens for many of us (and a sign your energetic field needs some tending). it’s an invaluable part of our living system but one that’s often overlooked.

column1: i created a free guided practice for you to clear and stabilize your energetic field because i’ve been hearing the same stories and symptoms from other women all week. click the link in my profile to listen. it’s about 45 minutes and incredibly potent. you will acquaint yourself with you energetic grid and repair your entire being. this is a cathartic process so please make sure you are somewhere quiet and where you are free to vocalize.
i trust you will feel more you when complete. in your body. still connected to feelings but without them draining your source power. it’s imperative that you take care of yourself at this time.
take some time in this dark moon and venus retrograde for your experience. blessings and all love.

column1: 308078;instagram;2018-10-07 19:56:56;FALSE;"i wrote this back when #metoo took life to the world.
“just let him... it doesn’t matter anyways.”
and it makes me cringe because that’s the cycle it’s always been.
we break down by repetitive beatings by hate
it can’t be like that anymore.
we can’t let that be the continuous narrative forever.
today we are fortunate enough to live in a culture that has grown the womxn’s voice and where we may question and protest without being sent to the gallows.
here’s to continuing our movement towards dismantling the patriarchy and our ideologies and inherent biases that allow for this to persist.
just something to think about this weekend especially as the supreme court moves into a new era in which we will see the repercussions of these actions for the next few decades.

column1: i posted this before in august but @rachel.cargle words are still ringing so true for me.
i can’t help but notice the complacency of so many people i know. good
column4: intelligent people who preach about love and light but take no actions to stand with oppressed people who need solidarity and need you to take action. i urge you to look into yourself & ask what your values are & if you aren’t putting your beliefs in to action do you truly value your beliefs? i’m sure a lot of people will be surprised when they dig deep and analyze who they truly are.

column1: i know it’s easy to get lost in our individual growth & individual struggles.. but that can only be an excuse for so long. i know paying attention to what’s happening in the world doesn’t always make you feel “the light” but ignoring the problems in the world will never make it go away. i tried!!
this is a time of communication. let your voice be heard. do the research (google is so easy!) and if you are confused on what to say here’s a start
column2: ask yourself: what are my values? do i believe rape is wrong? how have i contributed to rape culture & through my silence during the #metoomovement
column3: do i truly want to be the change?? am i registered to vote???

column1: i know people that have probably never thought about sexism
column3: classism.. i’m mostly talking to my hippy friends
column4: women who don’t feel there silence is contributing to rape culture
column5: and white men who sit comfy in there privilege...

column1: you may think you are free & that if you don’t pay attention to issues everything will be ok
column2: but all you’re really doing is sitting in your privilege while you & other people suffer. is this the person you want to be?

column1: 308126;instagram;2018-10-07 18:14:03;FALSE;"i actually wrote this the day i watched #drchristineblaseyford’s testimony last week. it’s me venting.

believe survivors. people who don’t understand what it’s like to be assaulted need to get rid of the idea that all victims are lying. it’s not true. i get it... there are some (much like our victimizers) twisted people out there. hell
column2: i just saw a video of a girl losing her mind on what i assume is her ex boyfriend and started keying his car. it was crazy!!! i get people do some messed up things in this world. but please understand that not everyone lies about something as devastating as this.

column1: i gain nothing by saying i am a victim. it makes things more difficult. when people find out they usually become extremely uneasy. i’ve lost job opportunities because of it. being a victim of rape is awful enough
column2: then to have it alter how people see you
column4: how you look at yourself and your way of life. it’s not a walk in the park by any means. i fought so hard
column5: with every fiber of my being to reclaim my life.

column1: i don’t want anyone else to ever feel as alone as i did. i want each victim to be able to get help recovering and to know that they can live an amazing life.

column1: 308133;instagram;2018-10-07 19:15:03;FALSE;"the past is with me in the now. the dataman that tried to teach me arithmetic. the buster brown shoes i learned to get around. i was born in 1971. the sticker on the box says $10.50. my mom worked as a keypunch operator coding mylar tape that went in missiles. i don't know what became of those missiles. she was unmarried raising me without emotional or monetary help after a privileged troubled man in court said he couldn't be the father and two other men that said they also had sex with her. without dna our lives were tossed to welfare and her good government job. in the 80's computers took over and she was breaking down to a state no one really understands. she left with a guy to california abandoning me with my grandmother. family that bought that dataman as a gift would 'take me in.' i'd be further indoctrinated into fundamental christian evangelism. including notorious televangelist copeland. i'd learn to calculate worth to fiat currency and fear becoming a ditch digger
column2: truck driver or janitor. i'd flunk the classes they demanded in word and desired emotion. i'm tryin to get along but i just don't fucking fit.

column1: my future. we can go to walmart and buy near $10 shoes. either zero inflation or we're slaving out someone. someone existing better due to their good government job. like tracy beyer. he's been a marine. he's toiling life in aerospece machining. he's actually treated about the same. maybe some days worse as these paradigms do to men and women.

i'm not paid to share this with you. i'm not suing any complicit people for any of the abuses while getting around since first stepping into those shoes manufactured for me. i am being vulnerable. i am real. are you?

column1: last night i went to a post-burning man party
column2: the same party i went to four years ago where i experienced a sexual assault while tripping on lsd. .

column1: i told myself for a long time that it was my fault because i was tripping. the truth is that i was so shocked the entire time that i completely disassociated. it was like i had no control
column2: no sense of what was mine and what was other people's.  this person at the time preyed on me
column3: but it took me a long time to see it clearly. that they actively saw how confused
column5: and young i was. this person only saw their own desires. they did not want to connect with me. they wanted to take something. .

column1: i went to this party as a kind of reunion with the shadow. to reclaim my space and being awareness to a community which is still hiding it's wounds.  many people want to believe that their burn is a place where everyone is free and caring about each other
column2: but that is not always the case. i've had multiple first hand and second hand experiences of this kind of male sexual vassaults at bm.

i got to dance in my own space. i felt free and whole and so aware of myself.  i had women come up to me and tell me that they loved the onsie i was wearing. we danced. we shared stories and witnessing about how important changing the culture is
column3: in all spaces.  i'm grateful for these connections
column4: these conversations. they help us to make real progress

column1: i'm wholey convinced at this point that burning man needs to evolve or it will continue to be a space of dominance for predatory behavior.  i wonder what each active participant in the burn might do if they actively looked out for this kind of behavior? if they were aware of this violence and took it upon themselves to create safe spaces? unfortunately
column3: but i wish it for all those who partcipate in this event so what happened to me and so many other women is reduced and eradicated. though i encourage radical self reliance
column4: i believe that also comes with bein radically responsible for our own behavior.

column1: thank you for reading this difficult story. love~

column3: hiding the truth about what was happening to me in order to keep a place over our heads. 2 people with estranged families
column5: and both working. i remember this christmas was his first comment
column6: i made a candy cane out of christmas lights. he came to fix something and he made a sexual reference to me. from the moment i reacted poorly
column7: his harassment and pressure to coerce me continued until i ended up working for him to pay the rent
column8: or lose my place. he forced me to go to his place for him to have his way with me. i hated every moment. he offered me alcohol and i refused because i did not want to make my girlfriend suspicious. i worked under the table refinishing antique doors and entrances. he put me on payroll after i “caught up” - 3 weeks after i broke my wrist falling off a scaffold and he coerced me to telling the hospital i fell off my bike. he invited me over - it was right after my broken wrist
column9: to tell me i will be kicked out
column10: all the money i paid through favours and working for him to cover rent was null and void. i threatened him with the police
column11: i changed my statement at the hospital and shared my story with wsib. he let me stay with everyone involved
column12: i paid the money back again with money orders working as a cook. he stopped threatening me and messing with me
column13: but not before threatening me with more lawyers and convincing me i didn’t stand a chance or that i had no proof. from this moment
column14: i’ve kept records of everything in life. my entire life i have hid my vulnerability and aimed for independence to avoid these situations again but it never works

column1: 308149;instagram;2018-10-07 19:20:39;TRUE;;"""...life was supposed to return to normal for me as if nothing happened. i did not feel safe to talk about it at that time. in fact
column2: i did not speak of the incident until many years later. as international day of the girl child approaches
column3: i am in shame of living in a country where women and girls are neither respected nor celebrated.  where everyday we must fight for the equality and dignity of woman and the girl child.  i can relate to all the women in india going through any form of molestation in their everyday lives and keeping silent about it. this is only one of the innumerable encounters i have had with men who are hungry for a piece of us and have absolutely no regard nor respect for women. in my eyes
column4: there are no laws and no system in place equally heinous enough in india to tackle this feat. i still live with the haunting traumas of past incidents.  as a woman
column5: how long will it take before people take me seriously...."" - debashree mitra (read her full story at pleasecheckmyblog.blogspot.com) -in case you didn't know it takes a huge amount of courage to share things like this! photo by @rahulzerg .

column1: it almost happened to me. i was almost gang raped. my story is too long to fit in this space. you can find it on my page with the annie lennox post.

i know the terror that stays with you from watching human beings turn into vicious monsters before your eyes as they prey upon you like a pack of wolves. i know that's why you still look over your shoulder to this day and probably carry a weapon.
i know the shame you feel in thinking you did something wrong when you know
column3: you did not. you know this never should have happened
column4: but you are made to feel like you are somehow to blame. and you watched your friends report it and not be believed. 💔

column1: i know the obligation you feel to speak up
column4: even i dont know it like you. i am one of the lucky ones who got away.  it's painful to even think of my story 20 something years later. no one wants to relive this. i can't imagine all that you have survived. it breaks my heart.😢 i believe you. ❤

column1: how dare these clueless idiots drag you through the coals when you have already lived every person's worst nightmare! they are the very ones who need to walk in your shoes. shame on them. 😈
you are brave to share your painful
column2: personal story in the hopes that your fighting will change things and make the world a better
column3: safer place. you are so brave to put your wounds on display that will never truly heal and that have taken you a very long time to learn to live with. thank you for leading this very real fight that shouldn't be a fight in the first place. you are to be commended in the highest regard. ❤🤗

column1: justice[just•ice]—do you rulers know the meaning of the word?_
do you judge the people fairly?
no! you plot injustice in your<own> hearts & you spread violence throughout the land.<duetothisveryreason therearenow>
these wicked people<whom> are born sinners;
even from birth they have lied & gone their own way.
they spit💦 venom🐉 like deadly snakes 🐍; they are like cobras that refuse to listen
ignoring the tunes of the snake charmers
no matter how skillfully they play.
o god[fatherinheaven]! smash the jaws of these lions
o lord[creatorofall&rulerofheaven]! may they disappear like water into thirsty ground.
make their weapons useless in their hands.
may they be like snails that dissolve into slime
like a stillborn child who will never see the sun☀️. god[ourfatherinheaven] will sweep them away
faster than a pot heats over burning thorns.
the godly will rejoice when they see 👮🏻‍♂️injustice🇺🇸 💪🏾avenged✊🏾👊🏾💯. they will wash their feet in the blood of the wicked.
then at last everyone will say
column2: “there truly is a reward for those who live for god[ourfatherinheaven & creatorofall]; surely there is a god[a father & all knowing creator] who judges justly here on earth🌎.”

column1: i covet my anger. i’m proud when i can feel it. it took most of my life to recover it from the anxiety disorder that came in the wake of sexual assault.

column3: it festers. as william blake relates in the marriage of heaven and hell

column1: i couldn’t express or even feel anger without feeling like i would go up in flames. so i disassociated. i stifled the anger and then boom

column2: i want to say that if you’re terrified of feeling your anger. i understand. and also
column3: there’s a way to win it back again.

column1: we have these embedded ideas of anger as exclusively destructive. but rage can be holy when we let it unify us. when we feel it because we refuse to see ourselves as separate from the injustice happening right before us.
the ancient egyptian goddess sekhmet is an example of how holy anger can be. how feminine. how filled with love. part lioness
column3: she’s the one who brought wars to an end.

column2: who took on the warlords and regime of dictator charles taylor and ended the civil war in 2003. they took their rage and made it holy. it was their love for each other
column4: that compelled them to take action. together.

column1: like the mothers of the disappeared in argentina
column2: who demanded an end to the kidnapping and killing of over 30
column3: 000 in the early 80’s. they confronted the deadly and corrupt junta with just their tenacity
column5: and the righteous indignation of knowing that love was on their side.

column1: my sermon for redladies today is fueled by sekhmet and inspired by all the examples of what can happen when we let our anger unify us in a love that compels is to do whatever we can to keep that arc of the moral universe bending toward justice. #redladies #sekhmet #rage #resist #metoo #ibelieveher";en;#Repost

column1: to all the men in my life
please reach out to the women in your lives today whether it be your mother
column4: or close friend and let them know you support them. give them comfort if they have been harassed or assaulted at some point in their lives. too many women in my life including myself have had to push the trauma aside from such experiences. feeling for so long their voices have not been heard. lets hold ourselves accountable now by showing support towards the women in our lives and let their voices be heard. stand up for what is right. we can move this country to where equality is understood as our basic human rights. #movethevote this #november

column1: 308278;instagram;2018-10-07 18:05:21;FALSE;so i had to delete someone i’ve been following for awhile now. if you’re doing keto you’re more than likely following him too. he’s had great success with keto and is rightly proud of himself. but increasingly i’ve been seeing post and stories where he belittles people who don’t follow keto according to the gospel of him. he’s even commented on one of my posts when he didn’t agree with something. that’s fine. not everyone does keto the same and what works for one may not work for all. i stuck in there because he did have such great success and i like to support and learn from others in this great community. he’s also a trump supporter which again that’s not my thing but i don’t belittle people who are. you go your way
column2: i’ll go mine. with all that’s been happening these past couple of weeks with brett kavanaugh and dr ford he has now been posting horrible things about dr ford. calling her a liar and a bitch and the like. once kavanaugh got confirmed he was gloating about how none of the haters were liking his post about it. again calling dr ford names. that’s when i decided enough was enough. i refuse to follow someone who can so easily belittle and  stomp all over the feelings of a woman who came forward with such disturbing allegations. again

column1: 308293;instagram;2018-10-07 18:08:59;FALSE;"me when i think about the state of the world right now. ⠀
deep sigh. i do have beautiful things to say about change and solidarity and healing at some point
column2: but right now i am just angry and frustrated. this sucks. it feels like a huge three steps back and a slap in the face that someone like this will shape a generation's worth of policy. that white republican women had his back. that fbi investigations can be such a joke. ⠀

column1: i've been reading through some #whyididntreport stories and had a good old release cry. i feel sad on lots of levels
column2: but what cracks me open the most right now is thinking about all the young folks who have experienced sexual assault and witnessed the president mocking someone who so bravely came forward. i wish i could send protective bubbles out so that none of us will internalise this

column1: throughout this whole kavanaugh shit show
column2: i have been wondering why this is striking such a nerve inside of me.

or new information that the powers that be don't give a shit about women's pain. we have a president who has been accused of sexual misconduct/assault/harassment by 19 women. we heard him on tape talking about assaulting women. ""grab them by the pussy"". he has a long history of treating women as things. we see him mock and discredit victims of assault and trauma all the time. this is not news.
dr. ford's testimony was especially powerful. yes
column3: her bravery and resolve struck a chord in me. yes
column4: i am disgusted by the way she has been repaid for her bravery. disgusted

column1: whenever i start spiraling out from shit outside of my immediate control
column2: i find the best thing i can do is to turn inward. get quiet and see what comes up.

column1: i really did not like what came up this time.
i think that the reason i am struggling so much
column2: why this is cutting so deep is because i feel culpable. looking back i can see how my actions/inactions have played a part in my own oppression. it's not pretty.

column1: how many times did i let someone get away with a sexist or misogynistic 'joke'? how many times did i hear/see women being harassed or reduced to objects and made no objection?
how many times have i slut-shamed another woman?
how many times did i not stand up for myself?
how have my actions or inactions contributed to emboldening men to continue to treat women like shit?

guys i am in mourning. i am in mourning for my younger self who didn't know better. i am in mourning for the girl who let herself be reduced to her body. i am in mourning the years i spent feeding into a narrative that oppresses my sisters. .
this has been so hard to reconcile. .
but a fire is raging inside of me. enough. no more. i cannot go back and change the past
column4: or was too afraid to speak my truth. .

column1: as a woman who’s been through a rape trial
column2: i speak from first hand experience when i say the process rips you from the inside out.

column1: i’m considered one of the *lucky* ones. the state took my case as there was enough evidence to “believe” what happened to me. .

column2: i didn’t feel so lucky. every angle of my being was attacked and put on the chopping block to label me a liar/whore/slut/a girl that got what she asked for. .

column1: i know what it feels like to not only have my body violated
column3: my psyche/soul twisted and fragmented and my heart broken 💔

column1: the only thing that got me through was the glimpse of hope that i might be a light for another going through hell. oh and the brothers & sisters that supported me
column2: you know who you are... thank you🙏

column1: i’m finishing up a writing piece about my experience in detail
column2: for my healing and any one else that will benefit. stay tuned. and if you need any one on one support. it would be an honor to hold space as we unravel the pain and open ourselves up to joy once more🌻

column1: 308353;instagram;2018-10-07 17:37:01;FALSE;"day 7 of #selfiechallenge - it has been a tough few days. i spent the past two days in icu while my husband recovers from open heart surgery.
it’s torture to helplessly watch the love of your life go through hell as he writhes in pain and all you can do is ask the nurses and doctors
column2: “can he get more pain medication?” they
column7: and come back with another syringe or pill. you hold your breath hoping that this time the medicine will bring some relief.

column1: then when you think you can’t take anymore
column2: the monitors start sounding an alarm. “it’s ok”
column4: ” they say. meanwhile they’re racing around getting new medication and ivs started. of course what you don’t know is that for them this is normal and while you can intellectualize and rationalize the words it is still terrifying.

column1: so you watch and pace and breath and then when you can’t take anymore you walk away for a little while so you can catch your breath. you know that nothing you’re going through is as bad as what he’s experiencing and yet you still hold your breath for him and clench your hands as his face contorts while another spasm wracks his body.
all of this is happening and you feel impotent and helpless. all you can do is show up and be present
while this is going on in your world
column2: you cannot ignore what is happening around you. you listen to the stories of your girlfriends as they share their #metoo moments
column3: sometimes for the first time. you feel as helpless to take away their pain as you did for your husband. you feel like you’re going to jump out of your skin so you go for a walk.

column1: you look for a place to carry the pain and sorrows of the world and you find this small tribute to peace.

this is the face of release and relief. this moment is when you realize that it will all be ok because places like this exist. that people still believe in love and compassion as strength. you recognize that sometimes showing up and being present is enough and that it will be ok
column2: that you’re ok and he’s ok.

column1: now you can breath because peace found you. #namaste #authenticliving #peacebewithyou #ibelieveher";;en;#selfiechallenge

column1: 308375;instagram;2018-10-06 20:50:22;FALSE;"a few minutes ago kavanaugh was confirmed to the #supremecourt by the senate. this is  a difficult time for so many women who have been #triggered by this entire process. i believe and stand proudly with #professorford #anitahill and all the women who have been assaulted or harmed in anyway by a man. i also stand in solidarity with all the protesters in #capitalhill today. luckily the anecdote for today was having good #mailday as i got these two 📚treasures #fuckthepatriarchy i leave you with this poem by the remarkable #audrelorde ✊🏽
moon marked and touched by sun
but when the sea turns back
it will leave my shape behind.
unrelenting as the curse of love
and if you would know me
look into the entrails of uranus
within my birth nor my divinities
wear me inside their coiled cloths
i am treacherous with old magic

column1: dr. christiane northrup is a multiple new york times best selling author and beacon in this age of western medicine slowly waking up.  we are more than just a body.  our mindset
column3: and soul affect our health in major ways.  would you agree that the health of our mind
column4: soul and spirit directly effects how our body is functioning?  for me this is a true gift of an interview because i have followed and learned from dr. christiane northrup for years.  her approach to health has been so refreshing for me during very hard times of physical illness (i’m all better now so no need to worry😘). i believe you might find her philosophy of western medicine refreshing too.  this interview is very fitting for the political climate we have been experiencing.  we talk about the importance of the feminine power on this planet and how we truly are collectively rising up.  we also talk about what some might call miracle healings of als and light workers in the white house.  this conversation effortlessly captures exactly why i love dr christiane northrup and all she is doing to pave the way in medicine on this planet!  enjoy!

column1: 308435;instagram;2018-10-07 17:07:19;FALSE;"bollywood actress kangana ranaut has alleged that she was sexually harassed by director vikas bahl. kangana played a lead role in his film 'queen.' the actress accused bahl of harassing her on the film sets in 2014. ""even though vikas was married back in 2014 when we were filming queen
column2: he bragged about having casual sex with a new partner every other day. i don't judge people and their marriages but you can tell when addiction becomes sickness. he partied every night and shamed me for sleeping early and not being cool enough
column3: she told india today in an interview.

column1: she revealed that the director would hold her tight and smell her hair. ""but still every time we met
column2: socially greeted and hugged each other
column3: he'd bury his face in my neck
column4: hold me really tight and breathe in the smell of my hair. it took me great amount of strength and effort to pull myself out of his embrace. he'd say 'i love how you smell k'. i could tell something is wrong with him

column1: in a recent interview to huffington post
column2: a woman crew member had accused bahl of sexual harassment.

column3: ""at that time vikas had come to me with a script about a gold medalist from haryana. when i supported the girl
column4: he stopped talking to me. i didn't mind losing out on a good script and i never called him either. i was determined to say what i felt was right. the matter was pushed under the carpet and i didn't hear any updates on the same."" ""i could tell something is wrong with him. i believe this girl. but what is sad
column5: is that now that phantom has been dissolved
column7: even though the girl asked for help long ago. at that time

column1: 308447;instagram;2018-10-07 01:31:25;FALSE;"he was my classmate. he was my first boyfriend. he was my first kiss at 12 years old. he gave me the mary j blige - what’s the 411? album for christmas. he was my friend. a few years later
column2: i thought nothing of letting the boy
column3: who i had known since 5th grade
column4: into my house when i was home alone. his cousins lived across the street from me. he knew my boyfriend. i had been to his little sister’s birthday parties. we watched tv and then the unthinkable happened. he was on me. my panties were torn and his fingers were inside me. i was on the floor crying
column6: asking him why. i didn’t want this. why was he doing it? i tried to crawl away
column7: he grabbed my ankles and drug me back to him. he was on top of me and i was crying. and then it was over. he just stopped
column9: stepped over me on the floor and walked out of my house. i was crying
column12: scared and relieved that he didn’t have sex with me. i only told my boyfriend that he tried to kiss me and i stopped him. i saw him in school every day. his girlfriend gave me dirty looks. 2 years later a classmate reported him for making inappropriate comments and either lifting her skirt or smacking her butt. i still don’t know for sure. our small christian school opened an investigation in response to her allegations. i was called in for a meeting with 2 teachers and asked about him. his mother requested that the school speak to me because i knew him so well. i was there to be a character witness for him... and the truth poured out. he was expelled. i saw him on a bus my freshman year of college.

column1: i haven’t told many people what happened. if he was nominated to sit on the highest court in our country i hope i would be as brave as dr. ford.
i never realized that i was lucky my school believed me. i had no proof. i didn’t know the date. i had no witnesses. my word was enough. in my small world

column1: 308468;instagram;2018-10-07 16:51:09;FALSE;"in honor of domestic violence awareness month i want to share my story with the world. 🌎 being completely transparent
column2: about 5 years ago i was in an abusive relationship with a man that i thought was ""the man of my dreams."" he turned out to be a nightmare.

column1: my boyfriend had a superficial perception of himself
column3: and an unhealthy relationship with his mother and ex-wife (also the mother of his two children.) he was angry at the world. depressed. he was a military combat veteran that served in iraq. he disclosed to me that he had ptsd but was not compliant with treatment not taking his prescribed medication. he snapped often usually after drinking heavily. i mistakenly thought i could love him through the anger.

column1: the relationship progressed and he moved from his place into my condo. that’s when the verbal abuse turned towards me. the final breaking point came when he threatened my life. he flipped out as usual. this time he punched me. he choked me. threw me to the floor. he punched a hole in the wall. he destroyed the furniture in our apartment. the police officers 👮 👮🏽 witnessed his actions. they saw the disarray in the house. heard him make threats. forcefully removed him from the home. responded to the repeated violations of the protective order to include him stalking me by showing up to my job and former residence. the officers showed up to court to testify. it took two years in court for repeated protective order violations and substantially assault charges filed against him by the commissioners office. nothing happened. 💔💔💔 the prince george's county states attorneys office said there was not enough evidence to proceed and subsequently stet-docketed the case.
the turning point to healing came when i let it all go and gave it to god. fast forward five years later. i am the ceo of two companies the next chapter
column2: corporation and success creators! i reclaimed my joy and found love within myself. i am now a vocal advocate for victims of domestic violence and sexual assault. i am a survivor! ~love

i just want to say that while i am sad
column3: and ultimately disappointed in yesterday’s decision
column4: i am also in awe at the incredible things happening. an extremely brave woman came forward and proved that our stories matter. this may seem strange because of the ultimate outcome but regardless of how our government handles it- look around. what i see
column5: what i am choosing to notice and give my attention to is the out roar of people (of all parties) in support of her
column7: and inspired by her courage. this to me is unmatched beauty and should not be overtaken by men in power making the wrong choice. this has not silenced the voices of fellow survivors and it has not shown us that we do not matter. our government cannot and will not determine our worth. this is not the last battle and we have more additions to this army everyday. so be with your loved ones in this time

column1: 308477;instagram;2018-10-07 16:53:55;FALSE;"i covet my anger. i’m proud when i can feel it. it took most of my life to recover it from the anxiety disorder that came in the wake of sexual assault.

column3: it festers. as william blake relates in the marriage of heaven and hell

column1: i couldn’t express or even feel anger without feeling like i would go up in flames. so i disassociated. i stifled the anger and then boom

column2: i want to say that if you’re terrified of feeling your anger. i understand. and also
column3: there’s a way to win it back again.

column1: we have these embedded ideas of anger as exclusively destructive. but rage can be holy when we let it unify us. when we feel it because we refuse to see ourselves as separate from the injustice happening right before us.
the ancient egyptian goddess sekhmet is an example of how holy anger can be. how feminine. how filled with love. part lioness
column3: she’s the one who brought wars to an end.

column2: who took on the warlords and regime of dictator charles taylor and ended the civil war in 2003. they took their rage and made it holy. it was their love for each other
column4: that compelled them to take action. together.

column1: like the mothers of the disappeared in argentina
column2: who demanded an end to the kidnapping and killing of over 30
column3: 000 in the early 80’s. they confronted the deadly and corrupt junta with just their tenacity
column5: and the righteous indignation of knowing that love was on their side.

column1: my sermon for redladies today is fueled by sekhmet and inspired by all the examples of what can happen when we let our anger unify us in a love that compels is to do whatever we can to keep that arc of the moral universe bending toward justice. #redladies #sekhmet #rage #resist #metoo #ibelieveher";;en;#redladies

column1: but the outpouring has been such a salve

column1: doing this very difficult thing has been for me a necessary step. i am no longer scared of ghosts. i hope that my story and those of literally millions of others can contribute to how we address this harrowing topic in our culture. so many of you have messaged me with your own experiences and i am truly sorry that we share this trauma. but the only antidote is taking our power back by being as open as possible
column2: and sending young girls and women the message that there is no shame in speaking out.

column2: in light of recent events in the united states
column3: i wanted to pull a card for all of us from my goddess guidance oracle deck by doreen virtue for some comfort and support. when i saw the card
column4: i smiled. we are not alone. we are protected and supported by the very powerful sekhmet
column5: an egyptian lioness goddess of destruction
column7: and fierce protection. she is the daughter of the sun god re
column8: and also regarded as a goddess of healing. ☀️

column1: she is with us now to not only protect us
column2: but to help us remember our own strength that we have within. sekhmet is here to say
column3: “you are stronger than you think you are.” she wants us to see ourselves as she sees us
column4: strong and victorious. if we focus on the negativity around us
column5: it can distract us and we can become bogged down with doubt and fear. now is not the time for fear

column1: sekhmet says that in order to manifest our highest potential
column2: we have to act from this deep strength
column4: and bravery that each one of us possesses. it’s time to see ourselves as goddesses and to stand with each other. sekhmet is with all of us

column1: i’m so exhausted from hearing over and over “if she was really assaulted then why didn’t she report it sooner?” the answer is in the question.
survivors know that reporting their assaults can ruin their lives
column2: and this is what high-profile cases like kavanaugh
column4: and weinstein teach us; that no matter when you report your assault
column8: and so on threatened for speaking up. many victims do not report sexual assaults right after they happen because they fear what could happen to them if they did. they know that it could threaten their careers
column11: etc. and it’s way more complicated than that
column12: because often the perpetrators are someone close to them
column13: and/or the survivor didn’t/couldn’t understand what had happened to them at the time
column15: or a million other reasons that would cause someone to fear coming forward
column16: or even just want to bury the feelings in order to move on and survive. it doesn’t matter how soon after you are sexually assaulted
column20: or who did it to you
column21: or what your political or religious beliefs are
column22: there is always the possibility that your life will be torn apart by reporting it. there is no perfect victim. there is no perfect time to report sexual assault. when another person violates someone and takes away their power of choice
column23: the least we can do is allow them the choice to speak out when they are ready
column24: at a time that is right for that individual.

column1: i was assaulted many times over the years- this isn't news to anyone who knows me. over the last few years ive been more open about my surviving instances of rape
column3: and sexual abuse. my younger self wasn't in a place to understand what was happening. now
column4: having gone and filed a police report to prosecute my abuser
column5: i've hit this gray-area- what is there to do? i have an eyewitness that can't be utilized
column7: and silence equals consent in the eyes of the law. my silence has silenced me. my inaction has made impossible any further action. i was discouraged and pulled the report
column8: freezing the investigation. it was exhausting re-traumatizing myself for hours at the station only to realize i wouldnt get my justice.

column1: this mess with the supreme court has brought back that feeling of defeatedness. its a reminder of how i felt when i realized my own experiences and my truths wouldn't be enough to put him away
column2: even though in reality it was all criminal to begin with.

column1: 308686;instagram;2018-10-07 15:26:32;FALSE;"my heart is heavy today as i digest the news of kavanaugh's confirmation to the supreme court. to think that 50+ of our elected leaders decided that a man who has been credibly accused of sexual assault is eligible to hold a lifetime appointment in an office that requires him to make laws about the same bodies that he violated...well
column2: it leaves me close to speechless. today i use my own platform to stand with victims of all genders to say that my heart hurts for you. and it hurts for me as a victim. and for my children who may one day be negatively impacted by this man who is too extreme to hold such a position without even considering his history as a sexual abuser. it has been an important
column3: yet painful transition to examine my own privilege and realize how terribly unjust our system actually is. people of color being shot dead in the street
column4: children being separated from their parents and kept in cages
column5: drug dealers serving life sentences while men like bill cosby will only see a few years behind bars
column6: a man being elected as president of the u.s. who has bragged on camera about violating women
column7: a president mocking disabled people and victims of assault
column8: and the injustices go on and on.

column1: i shared a video clip from trevor noah on my fb profile yesterday
column2: and i hope you all can watch it at some point. but i'd also like to share a little piece of what i wrote in response to watching it...

column1: and for those of you who are willing to dismiss a victim's story as being too little too late
column2: or too hysterical about something little that ""all teenage boys do""
column3: i implore you to remember the reasons why victims are so hesitant to come forward in the first place...

column1: it's because of people like you.
stop turning the victim into the villain in order to soothe your cognitive dissonance for following someone who undermines your personal rights. when you stop blaming the victims
column2: they won't need to delay reporting their assaults
column3: and the abusers will start being held accountable
column4: and a culture shift will happen in which boys and young men will learn that asserting their sexual desires on an unwilling party is actually wrong
column5: and then true healing can begin.""

column1: i wish i had an answer to these questions. i don’t. but still there are lessons to be learned. i think that we won’t miraculously arrive in a world in which people all of the sudden practice self-accountability or hold others accountable. that’s why it’s so important to start with yourself. for me this means that i will use my privilege as a white cis woman to speak up in situations of injustice or call in people for tapping into sexist
column2: racist and other problematic discourses - still struggling with this often times
column3: because i always feel like i am lacking information or the right words - but getting comfortable with feeling uncomfortable is a small price to pay. i also keep educating myself on these issues
column4: listening especially to the voices of pocs and members of the lgbtiq+ community. i also try to address my own privileges
column5: not getting defensive when people call me in. it’s constant work i have to put in
column7: exhausting and not exactly rewarding. but we shouldn’t expect rewards for doing the right thing. i am not even sure why i am putting this out there
column8: but i guess since i have so many wonderful people listening to my thoughts
column9: i might as well talk about this publicly. 🖤💭✨

column1: the last weeks have been incredibly triggering for so many survivors of sexual assault. it was so clear what the right and just course of action was; but those in power simply don't care. they have their own agenda.
i really don't know what to say as it all seems surreal. a bad dream that we will wake up from.
here's the only thing i know. times like these we can neglect our needs. we can isolate ourselves. we can question what is safe.

these are the times we need to find connection. we need to be surrounded by those who understand. we need to find ways to resource what we are experiencing and there are so many great ways on #regulate4resilience. to come back to our centre. to bring us back into our capacity to cope; our window of tolerance.
we can look to the women paving the way through their vulnerability and strength; women like dr. christine blasey ford. we can become those women.
this is what self care looks like for me today. moving my body to bring me back to centre
column2: to feel the strength in my body and to clear my mind... and offload some rage. wading through the shit and rebuilding as i go.

column1: so let’s talk about losing the field.

column5: and victim blaming as twists to keep the reader interested absolutely infuriated me and i genuinely considered shredding the book and setting fire to the scraps.

column1: i’m sorry but this book is exactly how you know you’re too old to be writing books for impressionable teenage readers. the ideas are so outdated and archaic that it’s a wonder this made it through the editing process
column2: let alone was published. i just... i’m speechless. what in her right mind made abbi glines think pedophilia and victim blaming were a good think to write about in the year of the #metoo movement. has she lost her mind?

column1: on top of that it was just so poorly written that i honestly thought she was going to end the book by telling the readers that the main character had healed his disability by believing in himself. i was just expecting something like that to happen since every other horrible trope had already been used.
i was truly disappointed by the lack of effort
column3: and the use of some truly awful tropes in this book. after looking forward to it for months i can honestly say it was a waste of money and time.

that's what @positivityangel would've told me if i'd messaged her about what's going on in my head. but she's in a different timezone right now so i am just channelising her thoughts.

there's a lot that's happened in the last few days. or i should say there's a lot that has come out in a last few days cause all of this has been happening for ages. we've all been really angry and i thought i can sustain this anger. i don't have a #metoo story
column2: i haven't suffered like so many of these brave women. so i thought i can hold on to this anger
column3: maybe even be angry on thei behalf. listen
column4: share and listen some more. but today morning my resilience came crashing down. i broke down a few times and couldn't understand what was happening. i signed out of twitter
column6: ate some good food and wrote...and no it doesn't mean that i am being an ostrich. i still know what's happening around me. but this little self care...this is what we need right now. while we have to keep checking on our friends...we also need to check on ourselves. ask ourselves if we're doing ok. do we have energy to deal with what's coming or do we take a break and get back when we feel ready?";;en;#JustBreathe

column1: 308869;instagram;2018-10-07 14:14:04;FALSE;"art and poetry belongs to the beautiful and brave @flwriting
in 2017 taylor swift went to court to counter-sue a man who sexually assaulted her. she was the defendant and not the plaintiff in the case because she had not originally pressed charges
column2: she had reported his actions to his direct supervisor in hopes of stopping him from using his position of power to assault someone else
column3: and he sued her for defamation. she counter-sued and won for a single dollar
column4: she showed up and fought for the sake of fighting
column5: she knew she had the eyes of millions on her and chose to use her traumatic experience to set an example for everyone watching that what had happened to her and what happens to women every day is unacceptable. she stood up for those who can’t. during her testimony she stated “i’m not going to let you or your client make me feel in any way that this is my fault. here we are years later
column6: and i’m being blamed for the unfortunate events of his life that are the product of his decisions—not mine.” and later
column7: when being interviewed for her part in the times magazine piece on silence breakers
column8: she was quoted as saying “i was angry. in that moment
column9: i decided to forego any courtroom formalities and just answer the questions the way it happened. this man hadn’t considered any formalities when he assaulted me
column10: and his lawyer didn’t hold back on my mom—why should i be polite?” of course i’m not surprised they swore in a sexual predator to the highest court in the land
column11: ya’ll let them make music and movies and play football and you still laud their work and you let them be teachers and preachers and car salesmen and lawyers and claim they are good family men who would never
column12: you allowed a rapist to steal the white house and sit as president of the united states.

column1: 308937;instagram;2018-10-07 13:22:54;FALSE;"many of us can’t find the words today and that’s ok. it doesn’t mean we are silenced or backing down. far from it. i found this poem by @amberrosetamblyn to beautifully capture what i know many of us are feeling right now. thank you for your healing words @amberrosetamblyn and thank you @amypoehlersmartgirls for sharing.
what i will be is devastated.
what i will be is inward tuned
what i will be is a temper’s plume
what i will be is a busted hell
screaming look me in the eye
what i will be is fury fine-tuned
what i will be is a drifted force
what i won’t be is beaten.
what i won’t be is forgotten

column2: done with the brawl of our soul.

column1: what i won’t be is complacent
what i won’t be is a coward.
what i won’t be is pierce-less.
what i won’t be is the give up.
what i will be is the shift in the air
what i will be is an eruption of movement
what i will be is here.

column1: so i began @blossombrownbeauty mental wellness yoga workshop with engaging in a ice breaker activity i facilitated called “life net”. i held on to a ball of yarn that was passed around in different directions to each attendee. due to there being some new faces
column2: i wanted to use this as an opportunity to get to know some of the new blossoms and their parents. each person was asked to state their name
column3: something that they were grateful for (because i do do believe that starting your day with intentional gratitude aides in your wellness) and lastly asked  participants to share a fun fact about themselves. the icebreaker was simply to allow the participants to get to know each other a bit . however the meaning behind what the ball of yarn created and symbolized at the end is what i wanted my attendees to take away from the simple ice breaker. the yarn created a “life net” . as you can see the yarn was stretched in many different directions and every person who held on to a piece of the yarn/string played a role. if they dropped their piece of the yarn the life net would break. essentially we all need sources of support to help us through life. the rope before them represents their life line. blossom brown beauty is comitted to being a source of support and we strive to be a lifeline to young black girls and girls of color to help positively assist them on their journeys . there are many young black girls struggling with no support or limited support and feel lost hence the rising rate of suicide among young black girls as young as 5 years old. blossom brown beauty once to help stop that. so i encouraged/challenged everyone yesterday to continue to be a supportive resource to others who may be in need or attempt to reach out for help if you are the person who may be in need. #blackmentalhealthmatters #mentalhealthawareness  #lifeline #lifenet #icebreaker #blackgirlsdoyoga #communityorganization #building #programsforgirls #ittakesavillage #therapy #resources #stopthestigma #minoritymentalhealth #menmentalhealth #awareness #educate #intervention #harlem #nyc #depression #suicideprevention #metoo";;en;#blackmentalhealthmatters

column1: við eigum einungis einn líkama og eina sál. það er á okkar ábyrgð að hugsa vel um okkur. það gerir það enginn annar þó svo að oft sé góðan stuðning að fá.

í mars fór ég upp á geðdeild þar sem geðhjúkrunarfræðingur hjálpaði mér að finna réttan aðila fyrir þetta mál. við tók tveggja mánaða bið eftir plássi en mikið er að gera í þessum geira sem og öðrum. heimsóknin í mars hughreisti mig þó næginlega mikið svo ég tórði biðina. maímánuður rann upp og áfallameðferðin hófst. átta skipti voru allt samt ég þurfti og útskrifast ég í byrjun ágúst. það myndi enginn hika við að fara til læknis ef um brotinn fót væri að ræða. í þessu tilfelli var það brotin sál sem þurfti að laga. þetta var erfitt en á sama tíma mikilvægasta skrefið mitt í ferlinu.
ég er komin svo ótrúlega langt. þetta mun og hefur alltaf haft áhrif frá því þetta gerðist. þetta hefur mótað mig svo sannarlega og ég horfi á marga hluti með öðrum augum núna

308999;instagram;2018-10-07 12:54:13;FALSE;it is easy to lose trust in a world where something like the kavanaugh shitshow is possible. and it is hard to speak out about abuse. in many cases you won't be meet with empathy but a wave of disdain. but still - speaking out is so important. i am certainly no expert in that. i often quietly tolerated all kinds of abusive
column2: shitty and disrespectful behaviour during my life. so at one point i set myself an #intention. i don't know if this is helpful for anyone else (i hope so of course) but i felt like writing it down:

column1: say something. say something if someone comes uncomfortably close. say something if a guy tries to make physical contact you don't want or harasses you. you don't have to be afraid to embarrass him or yourself. speak out loud and clear. say something if he pressures for sex
column2: makes nasty jokes or crosses your boundaries. stay strong even if he gets angry. say something if he is mean or behaves like a bully. say no. say something if he makes critical comments about your look
column4: age or personality. say something if he objectifies you or other women
column5: no matter how widely this behaviour seems to be accepted in society. it is not okay. don't tolerate it. listen to that inner voice that tells you something is wrong and speak out. if you fail to speak out when you should have done it don't beat yourself up but try again. again and again. maybe change is possible
column6: maybe not. but you spoke out and have done your bit. it will set you free. .
